title: When was the last time you felt good about yourself? - Quora

response.answer_text: Today, I woke up. Today, I woke up and in one fluid motion, I got out of bed. I got out of bed and I took a shower not because I had to but because I wanted to, because I wanted to feel good about myself. I got out of the shower and instead of hurriedly getting dressed, I stopped in the mirror and stared at myself, taking myself in just how I am. The way my stomach sticks out just a little. The way my hips curve and the way my shoulders stand. The way my knees point in and my ribs point out and the way my whole body jiggles when I move. I took it all in and I saw that it was good. It was me and for all the abuses I could shout or all the curses I could spit, it would still be me. I accepted that this was me, on this day, and that there was nothing I could change. It was good. I put on my favorite underwear and my cutest black dress and I toiled over my eyeliner until it was just right. I smiled. My eyes were different sizes and my teeth were imperfect and my hair was frizzy and I was human. I was splendidly, unfixably, human. I went through my day and I’m convinced that at least one hundred people wanted to date me and another hundred wanted to be me. Even with the (often uncomfortable) way my thighs rubbed together or the convoluted directions my hair chose to take, I was indomitable. I was powerful. I was beautiful. I was profound. Today, I felt good about myself because I woke up and in one fluid motion, I got out of bed. I got out of bed and I took a shower and I took every action today because I wanted to, because I wanted to feel good about myself. I savor today because I know that tomorrow, I could wake up and spend all of my energy on getting out of bed. I could wake up and not get out of bed at all. I could not wake up. Today, I got out of bed in one fluid motion and that is reason enough for me to feel good about myself.

This morning. I got out of bed after only an hour of sleep, had breakfast, and came to school. This sounds pretty routine, (even the sleep thing: I’m a borderline insomniac,) but the reason it was so much harder was because of these pictures, which I rediscovered yesterday:   Names crossed out for privacy. These are from back when I was 13., from the website that was the biggest fad at the time; Ask and Answer - ASKfm . And I wasn’t popular, as you can tell. I was also considered one of the ugliest people in the grade. I know that that’s what destroyed my perception of myself, and to this day I strongly believe I’m ugly. No matter what you say or do, I won’t be able to see it. I won’t be able to see past this. Now, 13 seems like ages ago, but I’m not even 17 yet. And that was the starting of my teenage years. And as you can see, they weren’t off to the best start. And these are just 2. I have a total of 25 in my laptop. People telling me my face looks like a monkey, that I resemble a teacher who was widely considered to be ‘gross’ and ‘ugly’, that my profile picture was disgusting. One time, someone sent me a message/question of sorts, saying ‘Hey gorgeous <3’. I loved myself back then, to be frank, so my reply was an honest ‘um, thanks man!’. But almost right after, someone went as far to say that no one would ever think I’m good-looking, and that I should stop sending myself these messages. My answers seem cool and collected, even seem to be brushing the OP off. But I know how much these hurt. I was afraid to cut my hair or change anything about my appearance; I even spent the larger part of my first class on the day I came to school with a pixie cut, crying in the washroom. Not out of fear of being bullied, but because of it. I went to school so happily, but as soon as I went, the jeering remarks were too much for me to handle. And this was all day, every day. And stumbling across these pictures yesterday pushed me right back to those days, when it was easier to cry than to breathe. I never want to feel that bad, so I picked myself up this morning and that’s what I’m going to carry on doing. Daily.

The past few days have been absolutely great. I suffer from depression, anxiety, executive functioning, ADHD, and obsessing over every single thing at work long into the wee hours of the morning. Let’s travel back in time, to Saturday. On Saturday, I went to get a haircut on lunch break at work, and I walked into Floyd’s 99 barber shop, which is actually a really cool place, because unlike my normal barber shop, which plays Rap all the time, of which I am not a fan, this place plays all kinds of rock from The Beatles, to Pink Floyd, Metallica, and everything else, even Fall Out Boy. I walked in and the barber said “Please tell me you aren’t just getting a trim.” I agreed to try something else, because this was what I looked like before:  And this was what I looked like after:  I know this is going to sound conceited, and it goes against all the fabulous advice to love yourself the way you are, but the way I looked after my haircut was a huge confidence booster, and I believe also helped my mood significantly. Now, when my hair looked nice, I wanted to look nice too, and so I started dressing well again, which I hadn’t done since the end of December, when I began a spiral of depression likely due to Seasonal Depression (on top of regular depression, yay depression!). I dressed like this the past four days, and I took at least one picture every day, because I felt so confident about myself, and I actually liked the way my body and my clothing looked.      On Tuesday, my boss, who is a very nice guy, and genuinely cares more about my well-being than the work I achieve, was talking to me in the kitchen and said to me “Wow, Tyler, looks like you’ve bulked up a bit! Your chest and your arms look like they’ve become larger.” I felt really good about myself. I haven’t bulked up that much, But I’m working on it, and the clothing that accentuated those parts of my body that I want to accentuate.  The next part might sound a bit weird to some, and I’ll admit that it is. I felt really good because I was hit on by a guy. I’m Bisexual, but I’m dating a guy. It seems weird that I am excited about being hit on. But the guy messaged me after seeing my facebook story and said “TBH you’re really cute *kissy emoji*” I replied “Haha thanks but FYI I’m taken” He said “Aww” “Well their lucky” Side note, he had no chance because I can’t date a guy (or a girl, for that matter) who has improper grammar, unless they were born in another country and English is their second language, as is the case with my boyfriend. Regardless, It felt really good for someone to respectfully state their attraction towards me. It made me feel confident and sexy. I’m kidding about the sexy part. Maybe.

My school manages to get into the Science Olympiad State competition pretty much every year. We always place high in Regionals, and are then sent to States a few weeks later. Yet, even after months of preparation and hard work, we rarely ever make into the top ten at States. The best we had ever done in the past competitions was to get tenth place. Here's a breakdown on how the state competition works. There are about 40 teams. Each team is amongst the top in the Regionals. There are about 15 people per team.Each person on the team does a few events (there are 25 events to choose from). Two people do an event together.There are three types of events. My teammates and I call them study events, building events, and lab events. Each event has specific rules and parameters which have to be followed.On the day of the competition, competitiors take the test and are graded on how well they did. Then there are tie-breaker questions. The events are spread out throughout the day.Once they are graded, a slideshow is made naming the top ten of each event. The top ten of each event get a medal.At states, the teams who placed 7–10 stand up and are applauded. Places 1–6 get trophies and plaques. Places 1 and 2 go on to the Nationals.On Friday, our team arrived at school at 6:30 to take the bus to the state competition. We arrived at around 3. Some of my friends had events that night. We all went to bed at around 1 AM because we’re such brilliant teenagers and decided to go swimming late at night (we got a noise complaint, if anyone’s interested). We woke up at 5, packed up, had breakfast, and took the bus to the school where the competition would be held. My first event was at 7:30. I thought I did okay, but knew that if I had more time, I could’ve done better. I competed in two more events throughout the day. Finally, it was time for the awards ceremony. We were all anxious to see if anyone medaled. And we did. I medaled twice, placing sixth and eighth. In one event, we placed first. Everyone on the team medaled at least once. We were elated and waiting to see if we managed to place in the top ten. After doing well in our events, placing at least tenth did not seem like an impossible dream. It was a feasible, tangible possibility. Before announcing the top ten, other awards were handed out. We won the award for “"Best Small School.” This surprised us, not because we did well, but because we had no idea we counted as a small school. We have about 700 kids in our middle school. At last, the top ten teams were being announced. Tenth place was called, then ninth. Our hopes began to drop. We thought that there was no way we could do any better than that. Eighth place was called, and then seventh. Sixth place was called down to receive a trophy. That team was us. We placed sixth in the competition, four places higher than the second highest place our school has ever done, received a trophy, making our coach’s (and our) dream come true. I was on cloud nine. It's such a wonderful feeling when all of your hard work and sacrifices pay off. A smile was glued to my face for the rest of the day. We did it. We got a trophy at States, doing better than we had ever anticipated, surprising everyone, but mostly ourselves.

Consciously, the last time I was feeling good about me was yesterday. I handled a conflict with another person, and kept my cool through it. This other person in the program got in my space and yelled at me. Since it was an employee of the program who was supposed to be helping me, I brought it up with her supervisor and we had a conversation trying to work it out. I wanted to stay in the program, but would only do so if I was respected on the most basic level. She didn’t acknowledge what she did, and made a lot of excuses. But I managed to stay calm and decline to continue the program. I stood up for myself, and kept my anxiety under control. For that, I have every reason to feel proud. Today, I have felt happy, but it wasn’t from feeling good about myself. I’m just happy from enjoying life.

It was yesterday morning, when I had a practical exam in Social Dance. We had five dances to memorize throughout the semester, and I didn't want to mess up as I was a former dancer in the past. I stopped dancing in my childhood because it got over in my head as a career I'd like to take. Mostly it was because I was full of pride and couldn't handle my mistakes well after a disastrous emotional break. The past three partners I had made me mature enough to take it easy, and to handle dancing at a rhythm my partner and I can take. We were at the fourth dance now, and I had a challenging partner. We had the same courses, yet somehow could not find each other in our home college. He’s had difficulty getting the right timing when he's nervous. We were fifth in line at the sign-up sheet, but got called out third in the exam itself. I personally thought the professor made it a challenge for me as I was the one leading us two. The first half of the choreograph was alright. We were in the beat, we were in-synced, until a fast transition we had to make got him skipping to a step in the future. I tided him over, trying to get back to the right steps. It was alright to count out loud. What mattered most was not missing any steps. Eventually, he was lagging at the last part. We ended our exam as graceful as possible, and exchanged apologies as soon as we were done. He kept saying he was sorry for being nervous again, knowing we had done well in recent practices before this, and I kept assuring him it was fine. Because it was. I was assuring him we did well, because we at least got the rest of the steps down. We did our best. And oddly, despite knowing I would get a lower grade this time, I was happy to have been with him. I realized at this point I was also getting back to dancing for fun. So maybe I didn't take it as seriously as the first exam with an equally passionate partner, but now I also learned to communicate more, and to step down from my ground when necessary to make progress. I was learning. I was growing. And the best part was I felt good doing it.

Today, from 11–12. Sometimes I have to work to feel okay about myself. Not today. I’ve got a free fourth period, and our Thursdays and Fridays are block days, so I spent an hour out of of my block period at Starbucks. I got a mocha. I sat down at a table, plugged in my computer and my phone, and checked all the apps that need wifi for ten minutes. I opened my computer. I did my English homework. My chemistry homework. My AP World History homework. I finished, feeling accomplished. I did more homework, homework I assigned myself. I studied the people in Starbucks. The mixed race girl with purple hair and piercings and the sweetest smile I saw today. (She told me she liked my outfit, and I told her I liked hers.) The old white man with his earbuds in typing furiously on a modern laptop that, I soon found out, had an app on it that made typewriter noises every time a key was pushed. (I asked him the name of the app, and he told me his grandson, a tech wizard, has set it up for him.) The equally as old Mexican man, short and solemn and almost grumpy, with a big old cowboy hat on and his youngest daughter’s sparkly purse hanging off his backpack. The barista, who shared a name with me, and whose birthday is one day after mine (although several years before). The two women, chattering like chickens, who ordered an Americano and a Frappuccino and swapped drinks like secrets. I wrote poetry about them all. And I felt better about myself in an hour than I have all week.

A couple of weeks ago, I was at a grocery store and as I headed down the produce aisle, I saw, lying on the floor in front of me, a fat black wallet. I scooped it up and looked inside. There were a lot of credit cards, a driver’s license, and quite a bit of money. I started immediately for the customer service desk, but when I reached it there was a line. To pass the time, I told the woman ahead of me that I had just found a wallet and showed it to her. We looked more closely at the license. She said, “It’s an African name, I don’t know what it is. But I think I see the guy right over there!” She pointed to a young Black man in the process of putting his groceries through the self service check-out. I went over to him and asked if he had lost a wallet. He gave me a confused look, then as he patted his pants pockets, his look of confusion changed to one of incredulity. I held up his wallet. “Oh, my God!” he exclaimed. “I didn’t even know I’d dropped it! Thank you!” I smiled, handed him his wallet and started away. “Thank you so much!” he called out as I left. “I really mean it!” No, he didn’t offer me a reward. I never expected one and would have felt awkward taking it. But he was so sincerely grateful that I felt GREAT! I felt great for the rest of the day, referring back to that little incident in my head, knowing that God sometimes gives us the little gift of being able to do something for someone else who appreciates it….and that is a wonderful gift to receive!

Honestly I've never felt good about myself. I grew in a broken home and I developed anxiety and anger issues. When I started school, I was a loner due to my parents not teaching me social skills. In middle school, I fell inside a web of BS and started to attract toxic people. I was a nieve middle schooler who just wanted some friends. I found out those people saw me as “easy” and didn't talk to me unless they wanted something out of me. Now as a high school junior, I have issues with girls and I never asked my crush to prom (eventually another guy asked her) or showed her my true feelings for her. I'm too shy. Anyways, I hope find true happiness one day. I got to turn to God. If everyone only knew the real me.

I used to like this girl and she was just…so awesome. Really interesting and funny, the conversations we had were great and she was so beautiful. Recently I lost a group of friends because of an issue with my house getting broken into by said former friends and since then i’ve been talking to other people more and we’ve become really close. The reason things never worked out with us the first time was because my frustrating friend ruined everything by calling her and talking to her about it which gave away how I felt. I knew he did that on purpose. After that it became awkward and we didn’t talk as much. Now that we are friends again, even though i’m not trying to make a move or anything it’s just so great getting to know her this well. She’s so much kinder as well as more fun then alot of other girls I know around school and when I talk to her I feel like I can really be myself. I don’t need to act differently like when I am with other people, I can just be me, you know what I mean? To answer your question, the last time I felt great was last night. We had one of those deep conversations that lasts a long time and it was so nice having someone to talk to who wouldn’t judge you, use you, and genuinely cared about you.

The last time I smashed a cho mo. And that was a few years ago. I'm not “allowed” to do the things I learned growing up “on the yard”. I don't know how to deal with issues that those of my age “out here” have to deal with regularly because I didn't mature out here by going through the things that you go through over the years. I went to jail when I was 16, and quickly learned that if you have a problem, with someone else, you can solve it by stabbing them. Its quick and it ALWAYS works. They do things a little differently out here. Again, AFTER having learned, over the YEARS how to deal with things. I'm placed out here and expected to instantly know all the things that a 40 year old should know. I'm supposed to go from 16 to 40 overnight. And if I get caught with 3 pieces of French toast in my room at the halfway house, (where it's against the rules to have food in your room) they will send me back to a maximum security federal penitentiary, were you HAVE to carry a knife every second of every day (if you don't your own people will stab you because you are a liability) for 10 MONTHS. And you better not get in ANY trouble while you are there, you know, walking around with 1,300 “worst of the worst in the entire prison community” while you are there. They get so worked up because of the things i do, but can't see the most difficult thing I have to deal with on a daily basis. All of the stuff I DON'T do. It's difficult.

The doorbell echoed through the house, effectively waking me up. I lift my phone, and touch the power button. The home screen lights up with the time shown as 5:05 a.m. I nudge my mom awake and ask her to go open the door so that I could roll over and catch some more sleep. I roll over, spreading myself over the queen sized bed like the badass starfish that I am and bury my face in a mountain of pillows. I think to myself, which idiot would ring a doorbell at 5 in the morning? Fortunately, that idiot is my dad who came back from his trip— and by that logic, the son of a idiot happens to be me. Amused with myself, I get up to wish him good morning and head over to brush my teeth. A good cuppa coffee, and some light reading later—I decide to shower. I'm secretly a bathroom singer, and today I sing while dancing to “It ain't me” by Selena Gomez. Wrapping the fluffy towel across my body, I walk out 35 minutes later— phone in hand and still singing. I sing “Pocketfull of Sunshine” by Natasha Bedingfield while scrolling through Quora, when for the first time I notice that the house seems eerily quiet— especially when everyone is awake. I stop the song on my phone, and listen for something, anything really. My house is never this quiet in the morning. Thoughts from murder to an apocalypse rage through my head, breath fluttering, I tell myself to shut up and listen. A few seconds later, I hear my mother tell my dad “She was singing again…” followed by inchorent murmuring that vaguely translated into “Did she stop?” to a girl listening behind a door. I haven't sung in ages. I haven't been myself ever since depression struck me like a lightning bolt, turning me into a uncertain calamity. I hold my phone teary eyed, staring at blurry words thinking about how I've let my condition define me. A silent tear falls down my cheeks— I wipe it away. My eyes flutter back to my phone as I read Dushka Zapata’s answer and a pun amuses me. I let her know, and she responds almost immediately. I smile— honestly, it's shocking how in a moment, I can go from teary eyed to amused smiling again. All I know is that for a long time now, I haven't been as happy as today morning. I hope it isn't the last time I feel this happy.

Today. Today, I got out of bed. I managed to eat two meals. I did my math homework and worked on a project. I took a shower. These things have been difficult for me to do lately, so although it doesn't sound like much, I feel good about myself for it.

I honestly can’t remember. I saw this question- and paused, because I could not remeber the last time i had felt good about myself. Proud. Happy. The vaguest of memories make me think that maybe it was more than six years ago. When i still lived in India- before i moved to Canada. Life has not been the most emotionally fulfilling here. This society values materilistic shit so much, and i don’t feel like myself. I feel like i have a mask on anytime i am around people, on social media, performing, talking, teaching… and it’s exhausting. No matter how much i do, i haven’t felt good about myself in a long, long time. And I don’t know what i have to do to get there again, except try my best everyday, and hope that one day, it will become enough.

Last week Saturday I was invited to a party. I did not see my parents for the entire week since I moved closer to work. I normally go to them on weekends since it is a tradition that we all have lunch together. My father grew more attached to me as I got older. Its not a secret that I can brighten up his day. His a deputy principal at a state school so his turning into a grumpy old man. I informed my mom that I won’t make it for lunch as I will probably be too tired after the party. I told them I’ll see them this weekend for Easter. As I drove to the party I received a funny text from my father. He sends me jokes throughout the day. I replied with a voice note telling him I’m on the road on my way out but I’ll speak to him when I see him. He replied with a good night my daughter. I made a U-turn and at 10pm the night I went to go knock on my parents’ door to tell them I’m home for the weekend. His smile when he opened the door, it made me feel good about myself.

My initial thought when seeing this question was pfffft, that’s a good joke. But then I remembered the one time I felt good about myself, and it was a couple days ago. I do theater, and I was recently in the production of The Lion King. I had gotten the part of Rafiki, the wise old monkey that carries a giant stick everywhere.  This guy! (Girl? I don’t know, actually) I had some songs where I had solos and I had some scenes. It was the best role I’ve ever gotten. And I made sure I played it well. But apparently I played it better than I ever hoped I would have. I counted (random fact about me: I count a lot of pointless things), and 27 random strangers came up to me and told me I did an amazing job and that I had a bright future in theater (with some old ladies thrown into the mix!). So many people smiled at me while they were walking out that I lost track. And I was stunned. That many people? I don’t deserve that much congratulations. The director even came up to me with her four year old daughter and said to me, “She loves the Lion King, so I wanted her to meet you.” I was just flattered repeatedly more than I could have ever imagined. One assistant director said that I did amazing four separate times, and I don’t know if she forgot she had come up to me before or I was just apparently that good. I was amazed, yet so happy.

Yesterday as usual I woke up from bed hearing the unpleasant sound of the clock. I woke up before my usual time of waking up, nearly at 6:40 AM. The reason I woke up early because I had exam and unfortunately my preparation was not up to my expectation. I revised, went to the exam hall and came back. Coming back to the dorm I decided to make the best use of my time from now on. Even after being utterly sleepy, I started doing my homework, I sat before the computer screen at a stretch for like next six hours and got done with all my necessary stuffs. I tried my best just to focus on only one thing and I did. It felt great! The moment I realized that I actually had utilized my time was the last time I felt good about yourself.

Oh, well. That would be just now! See, I posted this answer here: Fred Shirley's answer to What are examples of Quora writers recording themselves reading one of their own Quora answers? I was left several comments by people saying how much they loved my voice. This is alien to me. I mean - it’s a voice, right? I hear it every day. I’m used to it. Wrong. I’ve got a few ideas about where this voice might take me, and what I might do with it. But it certainly made me feel good about myself.

You all might be wondering how’s the pik related to the question. Okay! Lets proceed. Actually in the pic, one with specs is my dad and the other one is me. I lost my dad 15 years ago in an accident. Since then I just used to imagine the scenario if my dad would be present here situation might be different and much better but destiny had different plans. So I was in 9th standard and a photo session for school diary was going on, we got our pictures. I returned home and began searching for something in almirah and there I found my dad’s folder and his pictures in it. I was completely mesmerised when I matched the 2 photos and that thing really put a smile on my face that I completely resembled my dad. Also after that day I started viewing myself from a complete different way. It was my happiest moment, I don’t know what in your case would be. And after that day I really mever felt alone. When extreme hurt or disappointed, I just sit in front of mirror and imagine my dad consoling me right in front of me. ☺

The last time I felt great was… yesterday, when I saw someone very attractive sauntering down the hallway. Hey! Maybe he’ll notice me! I thought. He waved, and my face lit up. Ecstatic, my hand shot up into the air and I gave a nice little wave back. He didn’t seem to react much. Little did I know that that would lead to my most recent moment of despair. My neck craned back and heat immediately flooded my cheeks; he wasn’t waving to me. Quite frankly, I looked pretty stupid.

Yesterday! When after a long month, overloaded with college submissions, I finally got a break. Few moments to sit back, relax and to do what makes me happy. I wondered what’s that? I sit back, slept, heard some good music and then around 12:30 at night, I sketched my friend’s potrait. Yes, after almost a year, I sketched. Earlier, I felt I won’t be able to do it since its been so long but gradually I did justice to it and the moment I finished it I just felt a bit good about myself. Moreover, when I presented the sketch to my friend, he tagged it as the best surprise of his life which eventually made me feel a bit more good about myself. What can be better than giving someone a reason to smile through your hobby? It simply made my day and his too.  This is the sketch of my friend with his sister which I made yesterday.

Today, actually. I have reached a year. It has been a long, long year, but it has arrived. One year clean. Thoughts of relapse? Absolutely. Almost relapsing? Yes. Relapsing? No. The scar still exists, but I still pass it off as a oven burn. I have not been a year clean since 2014. Longest stretch has been 20 months. It feels good to be clean. Of course, it is not without a price. But, I can deal with other’s rants about my choices as long as I do not have those temptations readily available. It is hard to be clean, but it is worth it.

Yesterday. I will tell you a secret. You will always feel good about yourself once you realise that you have someone to count on. Someone who will listen to you but will not judge. Now who is this for me? Her!  Yup. My dog. We don't share a very close bond (she is closer to my parents). But whenever she wants to play, she comes to me. At times she senses that I am sad. So yesterday, someone made me feel really bad about myself. On coming back home, I started doing all the work I had to do. I was obviously tensed. She (my dog) probably sensed it. In the evening, when I was sitting all by myself, I called her to play with me. Surprisingly, she came at once. Usually she ignores my calls! It could be a coincidence. But it made me feel good. We all crave that feeling of acceptance at times but we forget that we always have people who love us. They could be our parents, friends or even pets.

This past weekend. Last Thursday, my newspaper class flew to Seattle for a convention. We’d been planning for this for the entire school year. We flew out Friday, went touristing, attended lectures and hung out with each other. We even had competitions, in which I did not do well. So, why did I feel good about myself? I went. I have bad anxiety when it comes to social situations, whether it be with my friends or strangers. In the case of this trip, I didn't know anyone really well. Leading up to this trip, I would feel kind of sick. I would have to talk to, room with and spend lots of time with people I wasn't close with. To say I was anxious is a bit of an understatement. But I went. And I had tons of fun because I didn't let my anxiety hold me back. So, yeah, I technically didn't do anything big or amazing. All I did was have fun for four days. And I'm so proud of myself for it.

I know this is weird, but the last time I felt good about myself was a few days ago, where my crush started hanging out with me when he saw me upset. Why was I upset? Ive been going through a deppression time lately and I know no one wants to hear me vent about these things But sometimes all it takes is some support from the people who you know care about you
Politically, when Barack Obama was elected President. Personally, when I regained my ability to speak.

Last time I felt good about myself is when I quit opiates cold turkey last year. I had been higher than I could imagine, every day, for the last 3 years and I finally quit. That month was the most amazing feeling month I’ve ever had. Now, I fell off the wagon, but a few months later I kicked it again. It’s such a proud feeling! It was the HARDEST thing I’ve ever done!

This is my first post So please take it easy on me. It is just a very short thing, I was waiting for my train to another station and there was no train in sight, so i decided to get something from the station tea stall and bought myself a packed drink. There was a woman standing and seeing me as i purchase, when i turned to go, she, who was maybe 45 or something called me(I am a mere 22 Y/o) ANNA(big brother in english) and begged for food, she didn't ask for money and this was the first time i saw in reality someone begging for food. As a normal Person i first waved her away and she just went without even a single word, then i realized she was not begging for money instead it was food!. I bought her food and she happily went, i didn't see where she went. But at that moment i felt good about myself. I don't even know how to finish this post, Thank you for reading.

Whenever I see someone with car trouble, I try to stop and at least offer to help. I’ve provided some jump starts, and changed some tires. I’ve been driving junk long enough to know that, even if they might eventually get running again themselves, a helping hand might be appreciated. Enough such people have helped me, that I consider this my duty to pay it forward. The last case was a couple of weeks ago, and some girl was cranking away at a decade-old Cadillac, and it wasn’t starting. It had gas. She had just filled it. The battery and starter were clearly doing their part, but fire wasn’t happening. Then she offhandedly tossed out the clue. “This happens every time I put gas in it.” No other time. Only when she has just finished filling the tank. I suggested she loosen the gas cap. She did, and the car fired right up. I don’t know what was wrong. Maybe she had the wrong (unvented?) gas cap. Maybe the ratchets let it tighten too much. I don’t know. But that pattern had to indicate some sort of pressure/vacuum issue in the fuel supply, didn’t it? So that was my good deed for the day.

When was the last time you felt good about yourself? Possibly the summer of 2005, when I was quite reliably informed that I'd made a positive impact on someone's life. It's possible that there has been some more recent moment, but nothing of significance.

I dont think this qualifies as important but it did make me feel proud of myself. Whenever my dad would stick his head under his truck to do some “repairs” when I was little, I would always follow him out to his truck to watch and hand him his special instruments. Once, during his daily “repair”, one of the rotaries broke down and nearly crushed him under the truck. His leg got stuck underneath the truck and he groaned in pain. Being a little kid, I got really worried and jolted towards our door, knocking on it furiously until my mother opened it. I think I was too much in shock to speak so I think I brutally pointed and signaled to my hurting dad under the car while my face was puffed with mucus and tears. My mother called an ambulance and my father came out well in the end. Just a few small fractured bones. I still remember when I tried to get on the ambulance with my dad, and all he did before he left was kiss me on the cheek and congratulate me on thinking on my toes and searching for help. The ambulance officer came up to me as well for alerting someone instead of trying to help my father on my own. He suffered minor damages because of that. I was very worried but also very proud of myself that day.

I deliver pizza for dominos out of a full size truck (that gets awful mileage I might add) so I had a tow rope in my truck. New years eve in the town I deliver in, it got insanely foggy and my truck has bright enough lights where I wouldnt drive off into a ditch or something. so I continued to deliver pizza while everyone else stopped because they were scared to. Going down the road on my last delivery of the night I found a older gentleman stuck in a ditch off the curb in his house and easily helped him out by pushing while he reversed out of the ditch. After that I drive about 50 feet down the road and see a guy asking for someone with a tow rope. His son was stuck in a ditch up the road and it wouldnt budge with 5 people pushing it. So going up there we hooked it up and pulled the SUV out of the ditch and over the curb that he went over. I lost my tow rope in the process because it snapped twise then we retied it both times. Luckily we got him out of the ditch and they drove home with me leading the way for about a mile using my bright lights in fog that you couldnt see more than 8 feet in front of you. Helping those people out made me feel good about my self and my life because I made a positive impact on other people's lives.
